\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  The majority's selective presentation of certain facts requires that I provide a fuller rendition of the circumstances surrounding the }{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**69]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  charged offense in order to address the question certified by the trial court. Defendant was eighteen years old when he committed the offense. His father had a history of recurrent depression, alcohol and substance abuse, suicide attempts, and a personality disorder requiring years of mental health treatment. Defendant's mother also suffered from depression. Other extended family members had had "nervous breakdowns" or had attempted suicide. Early on, defendant was diagnosed with emotional and behavioral disabilities that affected his school work. The diagnoses included adjustment disorder with mixed emotional features, mixed receptive-expressive language disorder, appositional defiant disorder,}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****73]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  and acute stress disorder.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_87}{
\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_87}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P70]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  By the seventh grade, defendant was exhibiting serious behavioral problems and was smoking marijuana. On separate occasions in 1995, he threatened each of his parents with a knife. Crisis services were called, and defendant was briefly hospitalized, after which he continued for some period of time in outpatient psychotherapy. In 1998, he threatened to kill his father after he was grounded for using the family car. Based on that incident, he was charged with domestic assault and placed on probation.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_88}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_88}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P71]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  In the spring of 1999, after another confrontation with his father that resulted in his slitting his own wrist, defendant stopped attending school regularly, left home, and began working full time. His drug use escalated after he lost his job in January 2000. In addition to regular marijuana use, he experimented with other psychoactive drugs such as ecstacy, hallucinogenic mushrooms, and cocaine. In July 2000, he began using LSD. Although he claims to have taken up to 300 "hits" in the ensuing two or three months, at least one of the examining psychiatrists opined that such numbers were unlikely because that amount would have prevented}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****74]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  defendant from being able to function at any level. Defendant was arrested twice in August 2000, the month before the killing. The first incident occurred when he engaged police in a physical confrontation after they tried to remove him from a private residence. The second incident occurred a week later when he tried to intervene with police officers who were confronting his friends because of their use of his skateboards. He was charged with impeding an officer, disorderly conduct, and resisting arrest.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_89}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_89}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P72]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  By all accounts, defendant last took LSD two to three weeks before the killing. He continued to smoke marijuana on a daily basis until three or four days before, and possibly again on the day of, the killing, but apparently took few, if any, other drugs during that period. }
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**70]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 Nevertheless, he began to experience more pronounced feelings of paranoia in the days leading up to the killing. Witnesses described him as constantly discussing conspiracy theories and feeling that everyone was against him. He believed that his friends were trying to pull something out of him and that there was "a society within a society" that did not include him. He felt like everyone was "in his}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****75]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  face" and wanted to kill him because they knew what he was thinking, particularly how miserable they all were. He considered them all to be "robots" who could not control themselves.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0
\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_90}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_90}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P73]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  He ate very little, had difficulty sleeping, and stopped going outside. He believed that he saw blood coming from his cat and that the cat was in pain and asking him to end its misery. On the evening of }
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[***1119]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  the killing, he strangled and stomped the cat to death after he thought he heard it say it was suffering. He imagined that, to be reborn, he had to collect souls and become a new deity. Not wanting to look at the mangled cat, he decided to start collecting souls immediately. He headed upstairs to gather the souls of (i.e., kill) his neighbors, but they were not home, so he went outside and saw the unfortunate victim riding her bike down the street. Although he had never met or seen the woman before, he attacked her without provocation and beat her to death.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_91}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_91}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P74]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  The toxicology report done the day after the killing showed residual marijuana metabolites in defendant's blood but no other legal or illegal drugs in his system, except those attributed to medications he had been given at the}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****76]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  hospital following his arrest. A court-appointed psychiatrist, Dr. Linder, met with defendant on five occasions at the Vermont State Hospital between September 29, 2000 and November 16, 2000, after which he filed a report concluding that defendant was insane at the time of the killing but competent to stand trial. Dr. Linder noted that defendant exhibited an abundance of severe psychiatric symptoms strongly suggesting that he had a major mental illness-either schizophrenia, schizophreniform disorder, or schizoaffective disorder-at the time of the killing. Dr. Linder also found limited evidence to suggest an alternative diagnosis-substance-induced psychosis with hallucinations and delusions-which he opined could be considered a mental }
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 disease}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0
\ulnone\cf3  "due to the incipient and unanticipated development of the condition while using significant substances for the first time." Dr. Linder concluded that defendant had been latently psychotic for years and that recent circumstances-including drug use-had set in motion a complete psychotic breakdown.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_92}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_92}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P75]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  }{
\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**71]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0
\ulnone\cf3  While acknowledging that drug use probably played a significant role in activating defendant's mental illness, Dr. Linder did not consider}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****77]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  defendant's substance abuse to be the primary factor in his psychosis because of the long period of disordered thinking before defendant began his relatively brief period of using psychoactive drugs. Dr. Linder also opined that defendant could not have known or predicted the magnitude of his psychotic reaction to the drugs he took. Dr. Linder concluded that, by the time of the alleged offense, defendant had reached such a delusional and psychotic state of mind that he could not reflect rationally enough to refrain from killing either his beloved cat or a total stranger.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_93}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_93}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P76]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  Based on Dr. Linder's report, the parties stipulated to defendant's competency to stand trial. Dr. Linder and Dr. Bertold Francke, defendant's treating psychiatrist at the state mental hospital, testified at a hospitalization hearing in the spring of 2001. Following the two-day hearing, the district court determined that defendant was still in need of mental health treatment and required continued hospitalization, finding, based on expert testimony, that (1) defendant's mental condition had been developing for many years; (2) a mental illness such as defendant's is usually a lifelong condition that often}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****78]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  requires cyclical hospitalization; (3) defendant is likely to have more overt psychotic conditions at different times in his life; and (4) his condition will wax and wane over time. The court explicitly rejected the State's attempt to isolate defendant's past behavior from his then-current mental state, noting that his improved behavior did not demonstrate that he was no longer mentally ill.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_94}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_94}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[*P77]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  Following notification of defendant's intent to rely upon an insanity defense, the State obtained permission for }
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[***1120]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  Dr. Albert Drukteinis to perform an independent psychiatric evaluation of defendant. In April 2002, Dr. Drukteinis filed a report in which he stated that defendant was suffering from psychotic thought at the time of the killing and thus was not able to appreciate the criminality of his conduct. Dr. Drukteinis concluded, however, that defendant had no prior history of a major thought disorder such as schizophrenia and that, in his opinion, defendant's psychotic state arose in the context of heavy drug abuse. According to Dr. Drukteinis, defendant had acted recklessly by accepting "the loss of contact with reality that the drugs routinely brought which was not altogether different}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[****79]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  than the psychotic state which they precipitated." Hence, Dr. Drukteinis opined that defendant's }{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**72]\~}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  voluntary drug use directly resulted in his psychotic state and the ensuing killing.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}
